We use a dynamic programming approach to solve the problem. We create a 2D array (dp) with dimensions (m+1)x(n+1), where m is the length of pattern string p and n is the length of string s. We iterate through the pattern string p and string s to fill the dp array.

1. If the current character in p is a '*', we take the minimum of the previous character in s and the length of the substring starting from the current character in s.
2. If the current character in p is not a '*', we add 1 to the length of the substring starting from the previous character in s.

After filling the dp array, we return the value at dp[m][n], which represents the length of the shortest matching substring in s.

The time complexity is O(m*n) because we iterate through both p and s. The space complexity is O(m*n) because we create a 2D array with dimensions (m+1)x(n+1). The energy implications are low because the algorithm uses a dynamic programming approach, which is energy-efficient.

